The available evidence consistently emphasizes that routine insertion of a nasobiliary drain following endoscopic clearance of the common bile duct in choledocholithiasis-induced cholangitis is not indicated. Instead, the focus is on achieving complete stone clearance during endoscopic procedures, typically guided by real-time cholangiography, which ensures adequate biliary decompression and reduces the need for additional drains. No evidence supports the necessity of a nasobiliary tube as a standard step post-endoscopic treatment.

